The NSF grant supported two national meetings of the Physics Teacher Education Coalition (PhysTEC) project.  The annual PhysTEC Conference is the nation's largest meeting dedicated to the recruitment and preparation of K-12 physics teachers. The conferences held February 17-18, 2017 in Atlanta, Georgia and February 9-10, 2018 in College Park, Maryland each attracted about 100 participants.
The annual PhysTEC Conference is an integral activity of the larger PhysTEC project (see www.phystec.org), and is central to the dissemination of knowledge and practices regarding successful programs at PhysTEC Sites. The PhysTEC Conference engages and supports faculty, administrators and staff in physics departments at colleges and universities to make teacher education part of their mission and address the severe national shortage of qualified K-12 physics teachers.
The PhysTEC conferences featured plenaries, workshops on effective practices, panel discussions by national leaders, a poster session, networking opportunities, and professional development opportunities for physics teacher educators. The external evaluator reported a number of positive findings that indicate the conferences were highly effective:


Participant-centered sessions that included concrete data and valued strategies;


Frequent use of effective professional development strategies;


High degrees of interactivity at conference sessions;


Equitable connections among many types of attendees;


Sizeable learning gains across almost all topic areas;


A strong sense of belonging and community among participants;


Support for follow-up actions through sharing of concrete strategies;


Enhancement of participants' motivation and confidence in their ability to lead change;


Inclusion of high school teacher perspectives.







